1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,040
 Now let's talk about browser events.

2
00:00:02,040 --> 00:00:05,240
 We've been talking about events all along.

3
00:00:05,240 --> 00:00:08,520
 We have done an on-click handler, which is a shortcut

4
00:00:08,520 --> 00:00:11,340
 to, in effect, register a click event handler,

5
00:00:11,340 --> 00:00:13,000
 but we're just doing it with the shortcut

6
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:14,640
 of the on-click attribute.

7
00:00:14,640 --> 00:00:16,520
 And then when we do a set timeout,

8
00:00:16,520 --> 00:00:19,640
 we're actually creating a timer event.

9
00:00:19,640 --> 00:00:21,840
 So the timer starts, and then when the timer expires,

10
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:24,200
 the event fires, and our code is run.

11
00:00:24,200 --> 00:00:26,600
 So we've been doing this all along.

12
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:29,400
 But there is an entire event registration system

13
00:00:29,400 --> 00:00:30,960
 inside the browser.

14
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:35,280
 And we can say, I would like to register an event

15
00:00:35,280 --> 00:00:37,360
 for something to happen on this tag,

16
00:00:37,360 --> 00:00:40,080
 and we can hook things in all over the place.

17
00:00:40,080 --> 00:00:43,680
 And there's a separate event registration system.

18
00:00:43,680 --> 00:00:48,400
 On-click is like a shortcut using an attribute

19
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:50,800
 that eventually registers the event on our behalf.

20
00:00:50,800 --> 00:00:52,160
 And that's why you see the little event

21
00:00:52,160 --> 00:00:54,000
 when you do the inspect element.

22
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,400
 And so if we take a look at the code here,

23
00:00:57,400 --> 00:01:00,960
 we're going to do the same thing that we did in 03event.htm,

24
00:01:00,960 --> 00:01:02,080
 which we've seen before.

25
00:01:02,080 --> 00:01:06,240
 And then we're going to do it again in 10-event.htm.

26
00:01:06,240 --> 00:01:10,720
 And we're going to show the more generic way of doing it.

27
00:01:10,720 --> 00:01:14,760
 So in 03event.htm, we have an on-click method.

28
00:01:14,760 --> 00:01:15,920
 We've done this before.

29
00:01:15,920 --> 00:01:19,080
 And it calls my func when that method is clicked.

30
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:20,440
 And if you do an inspect element,

31
00:01:20,440 --> 00:01:25,240
 you see that that anchor tag has an event on it.

32
00:01:25,240 --> 00:01:29,120
 The kind of more pure way to do it,

33
00:01:29,120 --> 00:01:31,560
 where we're really explicitly registering the event--

34
00:01:31,560 --> 00:01:34,840
 these two things are front-ends and purposes equivalent--

35
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:38,080
 is we're going to, instead of having the on-click method

36
00:01:38,080 --> 00:01:40,560
 on the anchor tag, we're going to have an ID equals zap.

37
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:42,040
 And again, we have to put the ID on

38
00:01:42,040 --> 00:01:46,000
 so we can get our hands on it inside JavaScript.

39
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:48,960
 So we create an H1 and a paragraph

40
00:01:48,960 --> 00:01:50,880
 with an anchor tag in it.

41
00:01:50,880 --> 00:01:52,280
 Then we start our JavaScript.

42
00:01:52,280 --> 00:01:54,800
 And the JavaScript starts by defining a function,

43
00:01:54,800 --> 00:01:55,720
 doesn't do anything.

44
00:01:55,720 --> 00:01:57,200
 It just defines the function.

45
00:01:57,200 --> 00:02:01,320
 And then we call document.getElementByIdZap.

46
00:02:01,320 --> 00:02:04,800
 Now, that is grabbing that anchor tag.

47
00:02:04,800 --> 00:02:09,440
 And then it calls an element method called addEventListener.

48
00:02:09,440 --> 00:02:11,240
 And it's got two parameters.

49
00:02:11,240 --> 00:02:14,360
 The first parameter is I'm interested in the click event.

50
00:02:14,360 --> 00:02:17,360
 I want to listen for click events.

51
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:21,040
 And when click events happen, call my func.

52
00:02:21,040 --> 00:02:23,240
 Now, again, first-class functions,

53
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:24,800
 there's no parentheses on my func.

54
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:28,080
 That is a function reference that we defined three lines

55
00:02:28,080 --> 00:02:30,400
 earlier.

56
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:32,400
 And so it accomplishes the same thing.

57
00:02:32,400 --> 00:02:35,440
 And if we look at 10event.htm and we take a look at it,

58
00:02:35,440 --> 00:02:38,480
 you see that the anchor tag with the ID of zap

59
00:02:38,480 --> 00:02:41,680
 doesn't have an on-click on it, but it has a registered event.

60
00:02:41,680 --> 00:02:46,440
 And that's because we registered the event using JavaScript.

61
00:02:46,440 --> 00:02:49,080
 Now, if we click on it, it does the exact same thing.

62
00:02:49,080 --> 00:02:50,680
 That event is triggered.

63
00:02:50,680 --> 00:02:52,800
 It looks up and says, well, when a click happens,

64
00:02:52,800 --> 00:02:54,080
 I'm supposed to call my func.

65
00:02:54,080 --> 00:02:58,200
 And so this notion of adding event listeners

66
00:02:58,200 --> 00:03:02,800
 is a more general purpose notion than simply on-click.

67
00:03:02,800 --> 00:03:06,200
 I like to think of on-click as a shortcut to registering it.

68
00:03:06,200 --> 00:03:09,760
 Now, you might say it's a lot shorter.

69
00:03:09,760 --> 00:03:12,640
 And one thing about JavaScript is it's a bit wordy at times,

70
00:03:12,640 --> 00:03:13,520
 right?

71
00:03:13,520 --> 00:03:17,520
 Document.getEventById.addEventListener,

72
00:03:17,520 --> 00:03:18,280
 a lot of JavaScript.

73
00:03:18,280 --> 00:03:22,080
 But it does what you need it to do.

74
00:03:22,080 --> 00:03:25,520
 Now, I'm not saying you shouldn't use on-click,

75
00:03:25,520 --> 00:03:28,880
 but I want to show you the more general way of doing it.

76
00:03:28,880 --> 00:03:33,120
 There are other kinds of events that we can connect to.

77
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:37,400
 And so in this case, I'm going to just have a header and no

78
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:38,520
 paragraph.

79
00:03:38,520 --> 00:03:41,440
 And then in my JavaScript, I'm going to create a function.

80
00:03:41,440 --> 00:03:44,740
 And in that function, I'm going to log the current height

81
00:03:44,740 --> 00:03:47,600
 and width of the window.

82
00:03:47,600 --> 00:03:50,840
 When this function is called, it's only going to log it.

83
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:54,800
 Now, what I'm going to say is window.addEventListener.

84
00:03:54,800 --> 00:03:57,160
 Now, remember, document.addEventListener,

85
00:03:57,160 --> 00:03:58,760
 that's a different thing, right?

86
00:03:58,760 --> 00:04:03,060
 Window.addEventListener is adding an event to the window.

87
00:04:03,060 --> 00:04:04,840
 Remember how the window is the thing

88
00:04:04,840 --> 00:04:08,460
 that gets larger and smaller and has scrollbars, et cetera.

89
00:04:08,460 --> 00:04:12,280
 So I'm saying I would like to register a bit of my code

90
00:04:12,280 --> 00:04:16,720
 to be called every time the window is resized.

91
00:04:16,720 --> 00:04:18,600
 That's what quote resized quote is.

92
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:20,760
 My func is to think to call.

93
00:04:20,760 --> 00:04:23,840
 So now what happens is you display this,

94
00:04:23,840 --> 00:04:26,560
 and then you start changing the size of the window.

95
00:04:26,560 --> 00:04:29,920
 And on your console log, it's zoom, you know?

96
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:32,660
 Window height, 135, 136, 137.

97
00:04:32,660 --> 00:04:36,960
 So as you're making that window larger and smaller,

98
00:04:36,960 --> 00:04:38,960
 your code is being called every time.

99
00:04:38,960 --> 00:04:41,360
 Now, why might you want to do this?

100
00:04:41,360 --> 00:04:44,280
 Well, one of the big things in website design

101
00:04:44,280 --> 00:04:46,240
 is to do what's called responsive design.

102
00:04:46,240 --> 00:04:50,580
 And that's as the thing gets narrower or higher or smaller,

103
00:04:50,580 --> 00:04:53,800
 like mobile, you want to change the UI.

104
00:04:53,800 --> 00:04:55,440
 You might have in a big screen,

105
00:04:55,440 --> 00:04:56,960
 you might have a more complex UI.

106
00:04:56,960 --> 00:04:57,920
 And then on a small screen,

107
00:04:57,920 --> 00:05:00,960
 you might want to have a more narrow UI.

108
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:02,240
 Now, often things like Bootstrap

109
00:05:02,240 --> 00:05:05,080
 take care of all this for us,

110
00:05:05,080 --> 00:05:07,920
 but still Bootstrap needs to get their hands

111
00:05:07,920 --> 00:05:10,260
 on the resize event so they know,

112
00:05:10,260 --> 00:05:11,640
 whoa, the screen size changed.

113
00:05:11,640 --> 00:05:14,540
 So I need to kind of tweak the markup a little bit.

114
00:05:14,540 --> 00:05:17,320
 So this is an example of a window event

115
00:05:17,320 --> 00:05:19,840
 that allows you to render an opinion

116
00:05:19,840 --> 00:05:23,880
 as to what you want to happen every time the screen resizes.

117
00:05:23,880 --> 00:05:27,900
 Now, another issue that's an important event to know about

118
00:05:27,900 --> 00:05:30,520
 is what's called the content load complete event.

119
00:05:30,520 --> 00:05:34,720
 Modern webpages are very, very complex.

120
00:05:34,720 --> 00:05:36,360
 I mean, the things I've been showing you

121
00:05:36,360 --> 00:05:38,800
 in this series of lectures are simple

122
00:05:38,800 --> 00:05:41,860
 because I want you to be able to see them on a slide,

123
00:05:41,860 --> 00:05:45,320
 but real webpages with menus and pretty pictures

124
00:05:45,320 --> 00:05:47,840
 and colors and spinners, all that stuff, right?

125
00:05:47,840 --> 00:05:48,980
 There's so many things.

126
00:05:48,980 --> 00:05:50,360
 You got to download the HTML,

127
00:05:50,360 --> 00:05:51,600
 then you got a bunch of CSS

128
00:05:51,600 --> 00:05:53,840
 and some images and JavaScript libraries.

129
00:05:53,840 --> 00:05:57,780
 And so sometimes you're going to just get like 100 assets

130
00:05:57,780 --> 00:05:59,200
 when you download a page.

131
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:01,640
 The first one is the HTML.

132
00:06:01,640 --> 00:06:04,000
 And so the problem is, is it can take a while

133
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,880
 for all these things to get orchestrated by the browser.

134
00:06:06,880 --> 00:06:10,240
 It reads the HTML, it sees a CSS, it loads the CSS,

135
00:06:10,240 --> 00:06:11,840
 it sees a JavaScript thing,

136
00:06:11,840 --> 00:06:13,600
 loads the JavaScript, it da-da-da-da,

137
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:16,020
 and then it's got some images and it takes some time

138
00:06:16,020 --> 00:06:18,880
 and it does this all interleaved

139
00:06:18,880 --> 00:06:20,160
 and in parallel.

140
00:06:20,160 --> 00:06:22,440
 And eventually you want to know, are you done yet?

141
00:06:22,440 --> 00:06:24,000
 Or just, are you done?

142
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:25,880
 And so if we take a look at a typical,

143
00:06:25,880 --> 00:06:28,160
 at the page of Django for Everybody,

144
00:06:28,160 --> 00:06:33,160
 we see about 30 requests and many requests.

145
00:06:33,160 --> 00:06:36,200
 And you'd like to know when that's all done

146
00:06:36,200 --> 00:06:39,440
 because you can't write JavaScript

147
00:06:39,440 --> 00:06:42,040
 that references a tag that doesn't exist yet.

148
00:06:42,040 --> 00:06:44,840
 Or if you have, you want to write JavaScript

149
00:06:44,840 --> 00:06:46,000
 that does something to an image,

150
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,680
 like changes its size or checks something,

151
00:06:48,680 --> 00:06:49,840
 or hides it or shows it.

152
00:06:49,840 --> 00:06:51,320
 You got to wait till the image is there

153
00:06:51,320 --> 00:06:53,640
 before you start messing with it, right?

154
00:06:53,640 --> 00:06:55,600
 So there is a special event.

155
00:06:55,600 --> 00:06:56,560
 It's pretty simple.

156
00:06:56,560 --> 00:07:01,280
 And in this, you use a script tag near the end of your body.

157
00:07:01,280 --> 00:07:06,020
 So, we have a function, MyFunk,

158
00:07:06,020 --> 00:07:09,880
 and in that function, the console log, the DOM is landed.

159
00:07:09,880 --> 00:07:12,000
 And then we're going to add event listener.

160
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:13,920
 And this is a document event

161
00:07:13,920 --> 00:07:16,000
 because this is DOM content loaded.

162
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:17,520
 Not window, but DOM content.

163
00:07:17,520 --> 00:07:19,240
 Document add event listener.

164
00:07:19,240 --> 00:07:21,680
 The event name is DOM content loaded.

165
00:07:21,680 --> 00:07:23,480
 That's a hard-coded string.

166
00:07:23,480 --> 00:07:25,460
 And I say, please call my function

167
00:07:25,460 --> 00:07:28,120
 when all the files have been loaded

168
00:07:28,120 --> 00:07:31,160
 and we're ready and the user can see the page.

169
00:07:31,160 --> 00:07:33,100
 And so in this one, it's really short.

170
00:07:33,100 --> 00:07:35,360
 It's just that that console,

171
00:07:35,360 --> 00:07:39,280
 the MyFunk happens after the content is loaded

172
00:07:39,280 --> 00:07:42,520
 and after all the derivative things have been loaded,

173
00:07:42,520 --> 00:07:44,260
 et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

174
00:07:44,260 --> 00:07:46,840
 (upbeat music)

175
00:07:47,520 --> 00:07:50,100
 (upbeat music)

